SIMPLE: fluster
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fluster
<hw>Flus"ter</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Flustered</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Flustering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. Icel. <ets>flaustra</ets>
to be flustered, <ets>flaustr</ets> a fluster.]</ety> <def>To make hot
and rosy, as with drinking; to heat; hence, to throw into agitation and
confusion; to confuse; to muddle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His habit or <qex>flustering</qex> himself daily with claret.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fluster</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fluster
<hw>Flus"ter</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be in a heat or bustle; to
be agitated and confused.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>flstering</qex>, vainglorious Greeks.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fluster</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fluster
<hw>Flus"ter</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Heat or glow, as from drinking;
agitation mingled with confusion; disorder.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Flusteration</ent>⟦br⟧
